The time course of injury-risk after return-to-play in professional football (soccer)

Guangze Zhang & Anne Hecksteden

1 Read Me

This is an R Markdown document which provides reproducible code for the core analysis in the manuscript, “The time course of injury-risk after return-to-play in professional football (soccer)”. This commented code aims only to optimize transparency of the current analysis.

2 Survival analysis

2.1 Create Surv Object

# Create sobj for all cases
sobj <- Surv(data_analysis$RTP_to_reinjury, data_analysis$Cens)

# Create sobj for severity of index injury
data_minimal <- data_analysis %>% filter(Severity_ini == 1)
sobj_minimal <- Surv(data_minimal$RTP_to_reinjury, data_minimal$Cens)
data_mild <- data_analysis %>% filter(Severity_ini == 2)
sobj_mild <- Surv(data_mild$RTP_to_reinjury, data_mild$Cens)
data_moderate <- data_analysis %>% filter(Severity_ini == 3)
sobj_moderate <- Surv(data_moderate$RTP_to_reinjury, data_moderate$Cens)
data_severe <- data_analysis %>% filter(Severity_ini == 4)
sobj_severe <- Surv(data_severe$RTP_to_reinjury, data_severe$Cens)

# Create sobj for playing position
data_gk <- data_analysis %>% filter(Position == 1)
sobj_gk <- Surv(data_gk$RTP_to_reinjury, data_gk$Cens)
data_def <- data_analysis %>% filter(Position == 2)
sobj_def <- Surv(data_def$RTP_to_reinjury, data_def$Cens)
data_mid <- data_analysis %>% filter(Position == 3)
sobj_mid <- Surv(data_mid$RTP_to_reinjury, data_mid$Cens)
data_fw <- data_analysis %>% filter(Position == 4)
sobj_fw <- Surv(data_fw$RTP_to_reinjury, data_fw$Cens)

2.2 Compute Kaplan-Meier estimate

# For all non-contact subsequent injuries
km <- survfit(sobj ~ 1)

# Extract information into a data.frame
df_km <- data.frame(time = km$time, n.risk = km$n.risk, n.event = km$n.event,
  n.censor = km$n.censor, surv = km$surv, cumhaz = km$cumhaz)

# Calculate hazard from n.event & n.risk
df_km$hazard_dt <- df_km$n.event / df_km$n.risk

# Calculate cumulative hazard manually
df_km$cumhaz_manual <- -log(df_km$surv)

2.3 Visualize survival function & cumulative hazard function

# Survival function
survprobplot <- ggsurvplot(surv_fit(sobj ~ 1, data = data_analysis), risk.table = TRUE, surv.median.line = "hv", censor=FALSE, legend = "none", palette= 'darkgreen', xlim = c(0, 360))
survprobplot$plot + labs(title = "Probability of remaining free of subsequent injury", x = "Time after RTP (days)", y = "Survival probability") + xlim(0,360) + theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", hjust= .5, size = 15), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray10", size = .3, linetype = "dotted"), axis.line=element_line (colour = "transparent")) + guides(color = guide_legend(direction = "horizontal"))

# Plot manually calculated cumulative hazards from Kaplan-Meier table
ggplot(NULL)+geom_point(data=df_km, aes(x=time, y=cumhaz_manual), col="purple") + labs(title = "Cumulative hazard function", x = "Time after RTP (days)", y = "Cumulative hazards") + xlim(0,360) + theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", hjust= .5, size = 15), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray10", size = .3, linetype = "dotted"), axis.line=element_line (colour = "transparent")) + guides(color = guide_legend(direction = "horizontal"))

2.4 Use polynomial regression to fit cumulative hazards

  • Note: Polynomial regression here is used to fit the stair-step cumulative hazard function, producing a smooth fine-grained curve which is subsequently used to calculate daily hazards as the rate of change (local slope) in cumulative hazard function.
# all non-contact subsequent injuries
df_km_200 <- filter(df_km, time <= 200)
Cumhaz_mod <- lm(df_km_200$cumhaz_manual ~ poly(df_km_200$time, 10, raw=TRUE))
## Check if 10rd-degree polynomial could fit cumulative hazard well
ggplot(df_km_200, aes(x=time, y=cumhaz_manual)) + geom_point() + stat_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE, fill=NA,
                formula=y ~ poly(x, 10, raw=TRUE),colour="red")

# minimal
df_km_200_minimal <- filter(df_km_minimal, time <= 200)

2.6 Calculate local slope of the cumulative hazard function

  • Note: The local slope of cumulative hazard function represents the day-by-day change, i.e., the daily hazard (or instantaneous risk)
# all
Cumhaz_pred_df_next <- rbind(Cumhaz_pred_df[-1,], c(NA,NA))
Cumhaz_pred_df_next <- Cumhaz_pred_df_next %>%
  dplyr::rename ("Cumhaz_pred_next"="Cumhaz_pred",
                 "time_next"="time"
                 )
Cumhaz_slope <- cbind(Cumhaz_pred_df,Cumhaz_pred_df_next)
# slope(x0) = (y1-y0)/(x1-x0)
Cumhaz_slope$Haz_slope <- (Cumhaz_slope$Cumhaz_pred_next - Cumhaz_slope$Cumhaz_pred)/ (Cumhaz_slope$time_next - Cumhaz_slope$time)
# Show first rows as an example
head(Cumhaz_slope)

  dplyr::rename ("Cumhaz_pred_next"="Cumhaz_pred",
                 "time_next"="time"

# slope(x0) = (y1-y0)/(x1-x0)
Cumhaz_slope_minimal$Haz_slope <- (Cumhaz_slope_minimal$Cumhaz_pred_next - Cumhaz_slope_minimal$Cumhaz_pred)/ (Cumhaz_slope_minimal$time_next - Cumhaz_slope_minimal$time)

# mild

  dplyr::rename ("Cumhaz_pred_next"="Cumhaz_pred",
                 "time_next"="time"
                 )

# slope(x0) = (y1-y0)/(x1-x0)

# Risk trajectory of non-contact subsequent injury
f1 <- ggplot(data=Cumhaz_slope, aes(x=time, y=Haz_slope)) + geom_point(col="red", size=1) + geom_line(col="red", size=1) + xlab("Time after RTP (days)") + ylab("Risk (hazard)") + labs(title = "Risk of subsequent non-contact injury") + xlim(0, 100) + ylim(0, 0.015) + theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", hjust= .5, size = 12), legend.position = c(.5, .88), legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"), legend.key = element_rect(fill = "transparent"), legend.title = element_text(face="bold.italic", size=12), legend.text = element_text(size = 12), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray10", size = .3, linetype = "dotted"), axis.text = element_text(size = 13), axis.title = element_text(size = 14)) + guides(color = guide_legend(direction = "horizontal"))
